The economic feasibility study carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the cross-border section and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains will be cut off at the same time.
At the time of the examination, it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains would not be opened to the original date.
This reduces the above-mentioned EIRR values.
The cost of both sections as of 31 December 2005 was Euro897 million excluding VAT, 27.4% higher than in the 2001 economic assessment.
In addition, there is a risk that Section 0805 will have a different, more complex internal process, which would affect the cost-effectiveness of the project.
The economic assessment showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway, with a daily traffic of at least 18 000 cars per day in 2010, is economically justified. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22 940 cars per day.
However, a study of diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Central Mountains predicts a traffic volume of 12,600 to 13,750 cars per day in 2007 and the project is below the economic efficiency limit.
A higher volume of traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Mountains is likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the initial economic assessment.
The mentioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the cross-border section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
The construction of the border section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomic.
The construction of the A 17 also saw an increase in costs, such as the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the D 8.
In the context of the overall economic assessment for the Federal Transport Route Plan in 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport assumed investment costs of around Euro320 million.
In doing so, it determined a benefit/cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, costs have increased to around Euro670 million and the benefit/cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.
Regardless of the parallel tests with the NKÚ in the years 2003 to 2005, the BRH had examined the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of the A17 motorway.
He noted that the authority responsible for the approval called for an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A17.
In the course of the examination, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the road construction administration of the excess fluidity of the landscape tunnel.
This has prevented Euro10 million in construction costs and Euro150,000 in annual operating costs.
When examining the first section of the A17, the BRH found that the construction was insufficiently prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
During the planning phase, the administration of the road construction refrained from recording the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschen wall, as it was difficult to access it.
It wasn't until the tunnel drive reached the wall that she caught up with it.
It turned out that the rock was more weathered than was assumed at the tender.
Costly measures such as anchorages, injections and stone-cutting protection nets for around Euro3.3 million were necessary.
The road construction administration not only bore the costs for additional, already necessary ironworks, such as securing the Dölzschen wall, but also for those that would not have been necessary if the building had been properly prepared.
These include expenses resulting from disrupted construction processes (Euro3.2 million), additional training of the propulsion team (Euro0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (Euro7 million).
This additional expenditure of around Euro10.7 million has no lasting added value.
The BRH took this and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to make better use of its specialist supervision of major road construction measures.
In this context, it should insist that road building authorities introduce quality assurance systems.
Benefits of cooperation for BRH and NKÚ The cooperation met the expectations of both audit institutions.
The BRH received information on the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both audit institutions developed a database on bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful for future audits.
The NKÚ found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and roadway of the D8 are not different from those of the A17.
The auditors from both audit institutions involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience, which will be useful in future audits.
